  "response": "While there are no definitive physical signs that definitively identify someone as an aristocrat, historically some subtle indicators might have included:\n\n1. Posture\n- Very upright, refined stance\n- Elegant, controlled movements\n- Confident body language\n\n2. Skin/Complexion\n- Pale skin (traditionally associated with not working outdoors)\n- Unblemished, well-maintained skin\n- No signs of manual labor\n\n3. Hands\n- Soft, uncalloused hands\n- Well-manicured nails\n- No signs of physical work\n\n4. Clothing/Appearance\n- High-quality, tailored clothing\n- Understated but expensive accessories\n- Well-groomed appearance\n- Subtle, expensive jewelry\n\n5. Physical Features\n- Some aristocratic families had distinctive features due to limited intermarriage\n- Certain facial bone structures\n- Maintained physical fitness without manual labor\n\n6. Demeanor\n- Calm, confident demeanor\n- Refined speech patterns\n- Subtle but noticeable self-assurance\n\nModern aristocracy is less about physical traits and more about lineage, wealth, and social connections. These historical markers are less relevant today.",
